Diagnosis.
Holotype
10.5 mm long for 30 chaetigers, body pale brown dorsally, with conspicuous white bands on segments 2, 8, 12, 17, 27, 31, 35, 39, 43, 47, 51, 53 and 57 (
Fig. 9A
). Lateral antennae nearly as long as prostomium; median antenna fusiform, 1/3 as long as lateral ones; palps as long as lateral antennae, palpostyles twice as long as palpophores; two pairs of dark red, circular eyes, anterior ones larger (
Fig. 9A
). Parapodia biramous (
Fig. 9B–E
). Notopodia bearing discrete cirrophore with sub-distal constriction and thinner distal region (
Fig. 9B–E
); with 1–3 forked notochaetae (
Fig. 9G
). Neuropodia bearing prechaetal lobe with long triangular projection (
Fig. 9B–E
), with about 23 supraacicular and 25 sub-acicular compound chaetae with bifid tips (
Fig. 9H–L
).

Etymology. The species is named in honor of the pioneering Japanese polychaetologist Prof. Shiro Okuda, who first reported this species (as
Podarke pugettensis Johnson, 1901
) from Japan dwelling on apodous holothurian burrows and described their characteristic color pattern.

Diagnosis.
Holotype
incomplete, 
5 mm
long for 35 chaetigers, body dorsally brown, with three thin pale brown bands on each segment, prostomium uniformly brown or with paler area around posterior eyes (
Fig. 4F
). Lateral antennae slightly longer than prostomium; median antenna fusiform and short; palps as long as lateral antennae, palpostyles twice as long as palpophores; two pairs of dark red, circular eyes, anterior ones larger (
Fig. 10A
). Parapodia biramous (
Figs 10C, D
, 
11A
). Notopodia bearing cylindrical, distinctly long cirrophore with conspicuous constriction at 1/3 of total length (
Fig. 11B
); 1–4 forked notochaetae, with short sub-apical spine and long serrated shaft (
Fig. 11D
). Neuropodial lobe with a wide, triangular postchaetal lobe (
Fig. 10C, D
) and two thick aciculae (
Fig. 11C
); neurochaetae typical of the genus (
Fig. 11E–I
). Pygidiun with a pair of long, slender anal cirri (
Fig. 10B
)

Diagnosis.
Holotype
6 mm
long for 42 chaetigers, body colorless. Median antenna subulate, as long as prostomium; lateral antennae similar, but slightly longer; palps similar in shape and length to lateral antennae, without articulation (
Fig. 12A, B
). Outer margin of proboscis surrounded by 10 triangular papillae (
Fig. 12C, D
). Parapodia sub-biramous (
Fig. 12E–G
). Notopodia with cylindrical cirrophore (
Fig. 12E–G
); cirrostyles articulated (
Fig. 12F, G
), alternating long and short; notochaetae absent. Anterior neuropodial lobes cylindrical (
Fig. 12E, F
); posterior ones long and stout (
Fig. 12G
); single spiniger compound chaetae present in supra-acicular position (
Fig. 12K
); modified falciger chaetae present along chaetigers 6–32, with very short, conical blades (
Fig. 12H, I
); those in remaining chaetigers with longer blades with expanded tips (
Fig. 12J
).
